<article>
    <h1>Too much fo&#xAD;cus on po&#xAD;lit&#xAD;i&#xAD;cal cor&#xAD;rect&#xAD;ness</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201028/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-28"><time>2020-10-28</time></a>
        - <span>FORUM</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Sin­ga­pore Peo­ple’s Party chair­man Jose Ray­mond posted on Face­book his views that the lat­est se­ries of posters by the Sin­ga­pore Kind­nesses Move­ment had racially pro­filed cit­i­zens.</p>
    <p>As the Sin­ga­pore Kind­ness Move­ment later ex­plained, the full set of posters fea­tured dif­fer­ent races in the same oc­cu­pa­tion.</p>
    <p>There is no need to put all four posters to­gether at all times just to be po­lit­i­cally cor­rect. Af­ter 55 years of in­de­pen­dence, have Sin­ga­pore­ans be­come less tol­er­ant and are so con­cerned about racial pro­fil­ing?</p>
    <p>Are we re­gress­ing as “one united peo­ple, re­gard­less of race and re­li­gion”? The im­por­tant point is to level up the in­come of all clean­ers, re­gard­less of race, and make their job eas­ier.</p>
    <p>Mr Ray­mond should not be overly con­cerned with be­ing po­lit­i­cally cor­rect. I be­lieve no mal­ice was in­tended in the posters.</p>
    <p>I hope that we are able to see our­selves as Sin­ga­pore­ans first, rather than be­ing Chi­nese, Malay or</p>
    <p>In­dian. We owe it to our fu­ture gen­er­a­tion to be racially blind in as many en­deav­ours as pos­si­ble, even if our iden­tity card states our race.</p>
    <p>Our at­ti­tude and mag­na­nim­ity to­wards fel­low Sin­ga­pore­ans will de­cide the type of so­ci­ety we want for our­selves, our fam­i­lies and our fu­ture gen­er­a­tions.</p>
    <p>Foo Sing Kheng</p>


</article>

